Title: Utah Governors Executive Orders and Proclamations
Article Text:
%newline%

This series contains the official copies of executive orders and proclamations issued by the Governor. Executive orders afford a method for reacting to and preparing a plan of action for sudden problems or changing events which require the Governor's prompt attention. Their issuance provides an established conventional means of responding to these events. Through the executive order%comma% the Governor also creates mechanisms to implement the regulations and establish organizations to perform activities of the government in some specific way. Proclamations are more broad statements of position. They provide a formal means to report to the general public that the Governor has responded to an event in a specific manner. Frequently proclamations are issued to pay tribute or to express formal observance of holidays or other noteworthy occasions.

%newline%
Browse Link: %newline%Browse all records in Utah Governors Executive Orders and Proclamations

Note: 1785.php has been marked for review (Null image description)
Title: Beat Poetry%comma% Broadsides%comma% and Little Magazines
Publisher: Published by Utah State University - Merrill-Cazier Library
Article Text:
%newline%

Beat Movement broadsides and posters in this collection were part of a revolution in self-publishing as artists and poets seized control over the dissemination of their work and took it directly to the people and the streets%comma% dodging the strong forces of censorship that permeated 1950s America. Diverse in size%comma% quality%comma% and quantity – from mimeographs to fine letterpress print – broadsides have been important vehicles for political%comma% social%comma% and cultural commentary on a profusion of subjects including politics%comma% free love%comma% the anti-war movement%comma% environmental consciousness%comma% civil rights%comma% free speech%comma% and more. The broadsides are critical primary research materials%comma% artfully documenting the dynamic social movements of the 1950s and 1960s.

%newline%
AMP Image Version: <amp-img src="../images/collection_images/collection1785.jpg" alt="Broadsides" width="370" height="207" layout = "responsive"></amp-img>
Browse Link: %newline%Browse all records in Beat Poetry%comma% Broadsides%comma% and Little Magazines

Title: Cache Valley Diaries
Publisher: Published by Utah State University - Merrill-Cazier Library
Article Text:
%newline%

The Cache Valley Diaries digital collection brings a sampling of these firsthand accounts from the Merrill-Cazier Library's Special Collections and Archives to your computer screen. More than just lists of daily reflections by Cache Valley residents%comma% these volumes also contain biographies and correspondence related to the individuals who wrote them. Some are typescript copies while others are the original narratives handwritten by the author. Each contributes to understanding 150+ years of Cache Valley experience.

%newline%

Note: 1787.php has been marked for review (Null image description)
Title: Collecting Memories: Oral Histories of American Folklorists
Publisher: Published by Utah State University - Merrill-Cazier Library
Article Text:
%newline%

Collecting Memories features the voices of American folklorists and aims to document the development and change in the field of folklore since the mid-twentieth century. A joint project of the American Folklore Society (AFS) and Utah State University (USU) (official repository of the AFS archives)%comma% this collection offers a descriptive listing of interviews held at USU and at other institutions. The USU interviews include transcript%comma% sound%comma% photographs and more. Interviews housed at other institutions are mostly analog and not available online; however%comma% links lead users to descriptive records at the owning institutions where in some cases transcripts are available.

%newline%

Title: Civilian Conservation Corps in Idaho
Article Text:
%newline%

The Civilian Conservation Corps (CCC) was a public works relief program that operated from 1933 to 1942 in the United States for unemployed%comma% unmarried men from relief families%comma% ages 17 to 23. A part of the New Deal of President Franklin D. Roosevelt%comma% it provided unskilled manual labor jobs related to the conservation and development of natural resources in rural lands owned by federal%comma% state and local governments. The CCC was designed to provide employment for young men in relief families who had difficulty finding jobs during the Great Depression while at the same time implementing a general natural resource conservation program in every state and territory. Maximum enrollment at any one time was 300%comma%000; in nine years 2.5 million young men participated.

%newline%

Article Text:
%newline%

Leo “Scoop” Leeburn was a famous Boise-area photographer who captured many iconic Boise images. His photojournalism career started in 1943%comma% and he took photographs up until his death in 2002 at the age of 81. His photos appeared in The Idaho Statesman. Leeburn has been labeled "the unofficial photographer-at-large%comma%" and "a Boise institution." His photographs show life in Boise in the 1940s from work to a variety of activities.

Title: - Collection in the Mountain West Digital Library
Publisher: Harold Mace was born and raised in Kanab%comma% UT. He was the only professional photographer in the greater Kanab area in the 1940s and 1950s. He was very civic-minded and recorded on film many of the events that happened in Kanab%comma% Kane County%comma% and the Fredonia%comma% Arizona area. He took the children's school pictures and his camera was at many school sports events. He photographed many weddings and family portraits. He also photographed documents for people to be preserved since copy machines were not available. Before he passed away%comma% he donated hundreds of photographs%comma% negatives and his early equipment to the Kanab Heritage Museum so that they could be preserved.
Article Text:
%newline%Harold loved gardening%comma% hunting%comma% fishing and camping with his family. He loved music and played several instruments%comma% including the harmonica and mandolin. He played with a small band for 20 years%comma% and played often at senior citizen homes in the Kanab and Hurricane%comma% Utah area. He passed away in 2008 but left a monumental legacy in photographs for others to enjoy today.

%newline%This collection is currently unavailable.

Note: 2102.php has been marked for review (Null partner)
Title: Leonard Feather Jazz Collection
Article Text:
%newline%Jazz journalist Leonard Geoffrey Feather was born in Hampstead%comma% England on September 13%comma% 1914. In the 1930s%comma% he arranged%comma% composed%comma% and produced jazz sessions%comma% and began to write about jazz for print media.  After moving to New York he worked with such greats as Louis Armstrong%comma% Dizzy Gillespie%comma% and Duke Ellington%comma% establishing his reputation in various fields of jazz.  Writing for famous jazz journals and authoring several books%comma% he was particularly influential in promoting Bebop.  Moving to Los Angeles in 1960%comma% he became the chief jazz critic for the Los Angeles Times. Leonard Feather died on September 22%comma% 1994.

%newline%The Leonard Feather Papers span the years 1900–1999%comma% with the bulk of the materials dating 1935–1990%comma% approximately. Included among the papers are photographs%comma% negatives%comma% scrapbooks and photo albums%comma% pamphlets%comma% notebooks%comma% sketches%comma% scores%comma% soundsheets%comma% correspondence%comma% clippings%comma% manuscripts (including those for books%comma% articles%comma% liner notes%comma% and radio and television productions)%comma% promotional materials%comma% research materials%comma% travel and teaching notes%comma% royalty statements and other financial papers%comma% lists of Mr. Feather's personal collections (audio cassettes%comma% records%comma% and video tapes)%comma% ephemera%comma% and papers related to Mr. Feather's last illness and documents gathered after his death.

%newline%

Note: 2114.php has been marked for review (Null partner)
Title: Stonebraker Photograph Collection
Article Text:
%newline%This collection consists of 540 photographs from the William Allen Stonebraker Collection%comma% which was donated to the University of Idaho Library in 2003. Stonebraker took photographs in Central Idaho's remote Salmon River and Frank Church-River of No Return wilderness at the turn of the twentieth century between 1900 and 1931. The collection contains images of the Stonebraker Ranch and homestead in the Chamberlain Basin%comma% his businesses (dude ranch%comma% pack train and dogsled operations%comma% mining%comma% big game hunting) as well as wildlife%comma% scenic views%comma% and early aircraft operation. 

%newline%

Note: 2172.php has been marked for review (Null partner)
Title: Montana State University (MSU) Historical Photographs Collection
Article Text:
%newline%

The Montana State University Archives holds over 34%comma%000 volumes and 1%comma%200 linear feet of archive manuscript materials. In addition to the manuscript materials%comma% there are also archived microforms%comma% sound recordings%comma% film and video recordings%comma% unique maps and historical photographs. Over 4%comma%000 of these historical photographs are of Montana State University from 1893 through the 1960s. These unique MSU historical photos include early 20th century campus student activities and clubs%comma% campus grounds and buildings%comma% historical events%comma% and prominent alumni%comma% faculty%comma% and administrators.

%newline%

In 2012%comma% Montana State University Archives and Montana State University Library Digital Initiatives launched the Montana State University (MSU) Historical Photographs Database Project%comma% an on-going%comma% long-term project focused on providing Montana State University historical photographs online and in easily accessible downloadable JPEG format.

%newline%
